so: Infant found with significant trauma this morning.  Appears that the adult females were fighting and this animal was wounded in that process.  Adults have been separated - each infant remains with own dam.  On initial observation, infant has multiple scabbed areas over entire face.  Both eyes are slightly swollen and face is erythematous.  Infant is clinging to ventrum of dam with arms, but is not using either leg at all.  Significant hemorrhage on right lower leg and foot.  Sedated both dam and infant for exam.  2-cm laceration extending from lateral canthus of left is full thickness through skin but with no deeper tissue damage.  A likely defect is grossly apparent on left cornea but unable to confirm to with flourescein dye at this time.  Applied ophthalmic antibiotic ointment.  Several small abrasions and very small lacerations noted over top of head - none requiring suture.  Two small wounds (~2 mm in diameter each) noted on lateral aspect of left stifle.  One small wound (~4 mm in diameter) noted on cranial aspect of left ankle.  Full range of motion of left ankle joint.  Wound on ankle appears to only be through skin without damage to underlying tissue.  Lower right leg is severely injured.  Multiple punctures and lacerations along back of lower leg and around ankle.  Crepitus noted on palpation of right ankle.  Radiographs show no apparent fractures.  Debridement of wounds finds that many wounds on right leg are to depth of bone with significant damage to underlying muscles and tendons.  Unable to repair tendons due to extent of damage.  Withdrawal reflex is present on manipulation of toes but unable to confirm ability to grasp with toes.  Circumferential laceration encompassing ~75% of circumference of tail in approximately the middle of the tail.  Wound edges are already nearly opposed and scabbed in place.  Elected not to debride for primary closure.  Clipped and cleaned all wounds.  Closed all larger wounds with 4-0 vicryl.  Area immediately above right heal has been degloved - unable to close.  Bandaged right ankle over this area.  Administered local anesthetic, systemic NSAID, and broad spectrum antibiotic.
a: Significant trauma to face and lower right leg.  Less severe trauma to head and left leg.  Concerned about depth of trauma to right leg and potential for long term or permanent lameness.  Also concerned about vascularity of tail distal to wound - skin is continuous only on underside of tail.
p: Monitor closely.  Administer antibiotic as prescribed and NSAID as needed for pain.  Expect some swelling of foot given bandage and degree of trauma present.  Expect laceration near eye to swell significantly as well.  Monitor for tail tip necrosis and for any evidence of use of right leg.  cc

so: fought with cagemate overnight. Severe trauma noted. 5 cm skin laceration over anterior medial left elbow, muscle affected; transection of partial muscle belly proximal to elbow on antebrachium.  0.5 cm dorsoventral laceration on antebrachium left, 2cm skin laceration medial antebrachium, muscle affected.  puncture medial left antebrachium and right medial antebrachium. 1 cm long laceration through skin on craniomedial right antebrachium.  multiple scratches bilateral forearms. scratch dorsal left head behind ear.   severe soft tissue swelling and bruising bilateral forearms. t=100.5 rr=36 hr=190. no other wounds noted. palpated for fractures, none found. crepitus  left carpus.  point tenderness noted medial soft tissue to elbow joint.
a: severe bitewounds soft tissue trauma to bilateral forearms. crushing injury to forearms has potential to affect kidney function.
p: separated cagemates.  clipped and cleaned all wounds.  debrided and flushed wounds on left arm with warm saline.  approximated muscle bellies on left forearm using 3-0 and 4-0 vicryl in horizontal mattress sutures.  left puncture wounds on left arm and right arm open for drainage.  closed skin over all remaining wounds with simple interrupted subcuticular sutures and simple interrupted skin sutures.  gave IV plasmalyte during repair.  begin treatment with enrofloxacin, ketoprofen, and buprenorphine.  recheck tomorrow.  consider radiographs if swelling persists.  MAH/ MH
